## Why This Is Asked
Tests ability to design idempotent, serverless onboarding with minimal IAM surface, a common beginner-safe pattern.

## Key Concepts
- Idempotent operations; DynamoDB conditional/transactional writes
- Least-privilege IAM for Lambda
- CloudWatch metrics

## Code Example
```javascript
// Node.js Lambda outline for idempotent signup
const AWS = require('aws-sdk');
const ddb = new AWS.DynamoDB.DocumentClient();
exports.handler = async (event) => {
  const { userId, email, transactionId } = JSON.parse(event.body);
  const params = {
    TransactItems: [
      {
        Put: {
          TableName: 'Signups',
          Item: { userId, email, signupAt: Date.now() },
          ConditionExpression: 'attribute_not_exists(userId)'
        }
      },
      {
        Put: {
          TableName: 'SignupsDedup',
          Item: { transactionId, userId },
          ConditionExpression: 'attribute_not_exists(transactionId)'
        }
      }
    ]
  };
  await ddb.transactWrite(params).promise();
  return { statusCode: 200, body: JSON.stringify({ success: true }) };
};
```

## Follow-up Questions
- How would you handle cold starts or retries that occur during a transaction?
- How would you test this in a CI/CD pipeline and observe idempotent behavior?

